Imagine asking Disney for $50 to make a movie that looked like a 1930s newspaper comic strip. &gt;&gt; mistake. &gt;&gt; At a time when the rest of Hollywood was chasing a darker, grittier look like Batman, Warren Beatty was obsessed with the opposite direction. He wanted to bring back the look of the Sunday spread. Also, for decades Dick Tracy serials and films were shot in black and white. [music] So, if this was the first time fans got to see a Dick Tracy movie in color, why not go all in and really make a statement? He wanted every frame to feel like Chester Gould's newspaper [music] panels had somehow started moving. As good as Batman or Superman was, they didn't look like a comic book come to life. It was a monumental gamble for Beatty, and he put his entire reputation on the line to bring this vision to life. We have to start with the original comic because that's exactly the look they were going for. When Chester Gould started Dick Tracy, printing presses were giant, messy monsters. They moved so fast and used cheap, fuzzy paper that if you try to use pretty colors or soft shading, the ink would just soak in and turn into a giant pile of mud. You wouldn't even be able to tell where a character's face ended and the background began. So, Gould and the newspaper used the boldest reds, the brightest yellows, and the deepest blues they could find. They didn't try to be realistic. They wanted to be loud. For a kid in 1931, opening that paper was like turning on a light bulb in a dark room. Gave them one more reason to look forward to Sunday. &gt;&gt; A big boss must have a vision. &gt;&gt; Now, how do you make a normally shot movie look like a comic strip? Beaty and production designer Richard Sylbert realized they had to rebuild the comics entire visual language from the ground up. The original strips relied on printed ink, cyan, magenta, yellow, and black. Gould was able to combine these colors to get green, purple, and orange. However, film photography is projected light based on red, green, and blue. To bridge this gap, the filmmakers created a hybrid palette called the color Bible. They chose exactly eight colors. The three primaries of ink, the three primaries of light, a single wild card of orange to represent skin tones, and black as the anchor. You do see other colors, but they are muted on purpose. Because this was pre-digital, they had to get it right in camera. The iconic yellow coat was dyed multiple times to achieve that specific glowing shade. What is incredible is that the colors are the exact same shade in every frame and scene. That's an incredible level of dedication and attention to detail. Every prop, costume, and set piece was painted or dyed to match these specific shades exactly. If something was the wrong shade, the whole production stopped. &gt;&gt; It only works if we're all in. &gt;&gt; To photograph this impossible world, Beatty turned to legendary cinematographer Vittorio Storaro. To him, every color had to have a purpose. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; It had to be explained in terms of energy. For example, Dick Tracy's dominant color is a nuclear yellow, like the sun at the center of it all. If Storaro used red on good guys and bad guys, he had to find all kinds of explanations for it. [music] If you want to know more about the cinematography of Vittorio Storaro, check out the video I made of his work. The biggest challenge was to ensure the colors didn't bleed into each other. To make this happen, he covered many lights on the set with special colored plastic sheets called gels. It was like putting colorful sunglasses over every bulb. To avoid blending, they did something incredibly time-consuming called layered lighting. Each light had to be pointed very carefully. One light would hit just the yellow coat to make it glow, another light might hit a wall in the background to turn it deep blue. However, by solving one problem, they created another. If everything had to be so precise, that meant they couldn't move the camera that much, mostly not at all. It's only during the action where you see the camera pans and tilts. That's about it. The compositions are comic strip-like and flow like a comic strip with a similar visual energy. This technique is rarely used for comic book-based movies, but it explains why Dick Tracy feels so [music] unique, like you're actually turning pages. The other problem introduced by layered lighting is they couldn't get the pulp comic look that [music] way. So, they went towards hard lights and leaned into film noir. They used tons of lights because they shot almost every scene with a tiny lens opening. When you do this, you get something called deep focus. This is when actors and backgrounds stay perfectly in focus at the same time, mimicking a crisp comic book panel. Storaro employed a silver secret of leaving a layer of actual silver on the film to make the blacks look like a deep dark ink. While using haze and smoke is sort of the norm on a film set, even when unnecessary, Storaro avoided it because it would mute the colors. Now comes the challenge of scaling this look to the rest of the city. [music] Instead of filming in a real city, they built a 28-acre version of Chicago as a giant toy set. To expand the city beyond the physical sets, they relied on 67 distinct matte paintings created by the artists at Buena Vista Visual Effects. These paintings bring a surreal dream-like atmosphere and play a huge role in giving Dick Tracy its unique look. In my opinion, these paintings are one of the finest examples of color mats in movies &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and fit the tone and texture perfectly. If you compare Dick Tracy to Batman, two [music] movies that use similar techniques for totally different looks and styles, Batman gave us a city we were afraid of. Dick Tracy gave us a city we wanted to live in. But blending real actors into these hand-painted backgrounds without ruining the colors was a massive headache. If they used a standard blue screen, the blue light would bounce onto the actors' clothes and muddy up those perfect shades. What they did instead is a forgotten special technique called the sodium vapor process. The actors stood in front of a white screen lit with [music] the exact same yellow light you see in old street lamps. A special camera with a prism inside split the shot onto two different rolls of film at the exact same time. One roll captured the actors in perfect color, while the other captured just the yellow background to create a flawless cutout. The real superpower here, because the camera only looked for one specific yellow light, the actors [music] could wear any color they wanted, even if it matched the background. You can't [music] do this with blue or green chroma keys, even today. Sadly, Dick Tracy was the last major Hollywood movie to ever use this mechanical miracle before computers took over. And because the movie looked like nothing else, Beatty wanted it to sound like nothing else. Up until 1990, Hollywood sound was still overwhelmingly analog. Dick Tracy broke the mold by helping usher digital theatrical sound into mainstream cinema. It gave audiences CD quality surround sound 2 years before Batman Returns or Jurassic Park. They took advantage of this by throwing out realistic audio. Fists didn't sound like real punches, [music] gunshots became sharp pops. By keeping every sound crisp and separated, they created a sonic world that felt just as flat, loud, and bold as the ink on the pages. And a world this loud needed a population to match. Larger than life characters you wouldn't want to [music] meet in a dark alley, but absolutely could not look away from. Beatty hired the biggest stars on the planet and then did his best to make them unrecognizable. Al Pacino delivered a performance so gloriously oversized it feels like he understood the assignment better than anyone. &gt;&gt; AND IF YOU AIN'T, FOUR of you. You can't buy the people. &gt;&gt; It earned him an Academy Award nomination and rightfully so. Madonna reportedly took a surprisingly small salary, yet she has an incredible screen presence and mystery that's perfect [music] for the role. The legendary Stephen Sondheim wrote five original songs to provide an authentic 1930s jazz atmosphere. One of them won the Academy Award for Best Original Song. If Madonna and Glen Headly represented the beauty of the era, the villains represented its nightmares. The contrast drawn we swing from a smooth Sondheim melody to a room full of monsters. For these monsters, the makeup was perhaps the most grueling part of the entire production. In total, they designed 21 unique prosthetic characters. These were full physical transformations allowing Pacino to chew the scenery through inches of fake skin. The movie is so thick with [music] talent that even the minor thugs are played by Oscar winners and comedy legends. It's probably the most expensive game of guess who in cinema history. The only real frustration is that so many of these characters are so memorable, you wish the movie had more time to explore them. But that may have been Beatty's larger ambition all along. Disney and Beatty clearly hoped they were launching a long-term franchise with a world rich enough to sustain multiple sequels. But that franchise never [music] fully materialized. &gt;&gt; Geez, Tracy, that was a lot of dough. &gt;&gt; This wasn't just a job for Warren Beatty. He grew up during the golden age of the Sunday funnies, [music] when his father read them to him. That emotional connection helps explain why he spent years pursuing the rights, why he fought so hard to preserve the comic's unique identity, and why he refused to dilute [music] its bizarre visual language for commercial safety. His involvement went far beyond starring in the film. He produced it, directed it, and personally oversaw nearly every major decision. The movie made money for Disney, but not the mountain of gold they needed to justify the headache of another one. Disney moved on. Beatty never did. To this day, he holds the rights to Dick Tracy with a grip that would make a mob boss nervous. To prevent the rights from reverting back to the original owners, he's produced bizarre television specials, essentially legal loopholes, where he appears as himself and as Dick Tracy [music] just to stay in the game. For Beatty, the battle for Dick Tracy is a lifelong crusade. Looking back at it today, Dick Tracy feels like a miracle. In an era where most blockbusters grey concrete, the vibrancy of this movie is refreshing. It truly doesn't look like anything else because it wasn't trying to be anything else. [music] It reminds us that movies don't have to look real at all. While a modern studio could technically recreate [music] this look using digital tools, the industry lacks the stomach to actually do it. It takes a specific level of creative ego and raw guts to commit to a vision this restrictive and this difficult. Warren Beatty made a film that refused to compromise, and that total commitment is exactly why Dick Tracy still looks like a billion bucks. Don't let the subscribe button hit you on the way out.

