In 1989, a major studio decided a minimalist bat symbol was good enough marketing for a superhero movie that many believed could never work on the big screen. That backfired immediately. Rumors spread that the studio was hiding the film because it was that bad, [music] and many critics were practically waiting in glee for it to collapse. The casting choice alone generated 50,000 angry letters from fans. And yet, when the first Batman trailer arrived, people went berserk. In this video, I'm going to break down the strange mix of risk, design, and creative obsession that makes Batman still looks like a billion bucks. But, in early 1989, people would laugh at you if you thought that was even possible. Daring? &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; No. Bat. It is easy to forget there was a time when Batman clearly only meant one thing to the general public: the 1960s [music] TV show starring Adam West, campy with bright colors. But, out in the world of comics, the character had already undergone a violent transformation. In 1986, Frank Miller released The Dark Knight Returns. Whatever followed was set in a gritty world of organized crime and urban decay. These comics directly influenced director Tim Burton's vision for the 1989 film. At the time, he was a young director with just two quirky hits. Hardly the obvious choice for a massive tentpole. [music] The studio probably thought he would be making a dark comedy film. This might also explain why they considered casting Bill Murray as Batman. And it might also explain their reluctant acceptance of Michael Keaton. This offended tons of fans. Michael Keaton was a comedy actor known for Beetlejuice and Mr. Mom. He was not muscular, but Tim Burton was not trying to cast Batman. He was casting Bruce Wayne. He wanted someone who looked damaged psychologically, who seemed like he hadn't slept in years. While critics complained about his lack of a heroic jawline, Burton was enamored by Keaton's eyes, intense, [music] restless, like a man walking on a razor's edge. Burton gave Keaton one very specific direction. Batman should talk as little as possible. during rehearsals entire blocks of dialogue were cut. Bruce Wayne was allowed more verbal freedom but Batman was a presence. Otherwise we wouldn't have got this immortal line the way it was delivered. What are you? &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; I'm Batman. The next problem was to make a realistic looking batsuit. [music] The traditional grey comic book suit simply didn't work on camera. So costume designer Bob Ringwood created a black rubber suit because spandex looked plain silly without the muscles. The cape was made from a heavy upholstery fabric treated with latex to give it a leather appearance. Nice outfit. It was a small engineering miracle first time but it had a major drawback. Keaton couldn't move his neck. If he wanted to look at something he had to rotate his entire body. How do you deal with that? Burton and Keaton embraced the limitation. The stiff unnatural movement actually looked menacing like a burden. It transformed Batman into a powerful almost inhuman silhouette. His personality reminds me of Nosferatu. The effect was oddly thrilling. The next problem was the Joker. All the variations of Joker since will tell you how hard it is to get this character right. If Keaton was a gamble, Jack Nicholson was the studio's insurance policy. He was already one of the most powerful actors in Hollywood. He negotiated a famously lucrative contract that included a massive salary, creative input and a percentage of the box office and merchandising tied to the Joker. It ended up making him the highest paid actor for a single film up to that point. Burton used Nicholson's personality perfectly. He was given the freedom to improvise and explode with energy. You can't look away when he's in the frame &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; which is most of the time. His permanent grin was a prosthetic appliance made of silicone. His purple suit required 30 yards of high quality wool imported from Scotland. The movie works because Batman and Joker feel like two responses to the same [music] trauma. One imploding hiding behind a mask, the other exploding with nothing to hide. But, the real star of Batman might be the city itself. Burton hired production designer Anton Furst, who designed Gotham City to be an architectural nightmare. It was a mix of Art Deco, brutally tall buildings, and decaying Gothic elements, all in black, gray, and brown. They shot almost exclusively on massive sets at Pinewood Studios for total control. Gotham streets were built slightly narrower, and buildings lean inward visually to create subconscious claustrophobia. Large portions of Gotham skyline were miniature models, not [music] just matte paintings. Speaking of paintings, there's tons of artwork everywhere, even in the photographer's modest apartment, and Joker loves to destroy them. They filled the sets with real smoke and haze to blur the lines and create a world that felt suffocating and corrupt, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; like it had been rotting for centuries. Only in this world could a man dressed as a bat make sense, or his Batmobile. It was constructed around two Chevy Impala chassis, powered by a massive engine. The sound of this engine was layered recording of a real jet turbine and a roar of a lion. Visually and audibly, Batman looked like nothing audiences had ever seen or heard before, kind of like a crossover between Blade Runner and Fritz Lang's Metropolis. Instead of flashy camera work, cinematographer Roger Pratt and Burton decided many shots would be surprisingly still. The camera often sits quietly while Batman enters the frame. [music] Criminals move frantically. Batman barely moves at all. You never see anything from his point of view. We're not supposed to relate to him. When the camera does move, it's slow, creeping dolly-ins, especially during the Joker scenes. This movement is subtle, but gives more energy to his scenes. When you 