ars every time T-1000 [music] reforms. Those shots were created by Industrial Light &amp; Magic using early digital compositing and fluid [music] simulation techniques. It's only used when nothing else can do the job. Most of the time the T-1000 looks completely normal. So their [music] strength is why it holds up because it doesn't have to carry the movie. The other reason is the film stock. By this time [music] Kodak came up with what's called a T-grain revolution with its EXR line of film [music] stock with unprecedentedly tight fine grain structure and incredible wide exposure latitude. The cleaner image helped the digital composites blend far more convincingly and it made filming in bright LA work without blowing out the highlights in the background. If you think there's uncomfortable levels of control, listen to this. When the T-1000 mimics a security guard or copycat Sarah Connor [music] in the steel mill, you aren't looking at CGI. You're looking at real twins standing in the same frame. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Yes, Linda Hamilton has an identical twin sister Leslie who wasn't an actress who was actually a professional ER nurse. Cameron and writer William Wisher completely subverted expectations by not showing a stylized world. They placed events [music] in the present. Arnold himself was confused by the idea but since Cameron had a lot more clout by then, Arnold relented. What's amazing is everyone remembers this film as having a massive budget which it did but a large chunk of it was spent on just buying the rights after a legal tussle and because the release date was already fixed, they had very little time. All the effects had to work the first time around or the movie could [music] have been a joke. But where Cameron didn't compromise was getting the performances just right. He's legendary for retaking his scenes again and again, [music] at one point spending five days just on Hamilton's close-up. The film was eventually three weeks over schedule [mus