Name a film franchise with a perfect record. I'm talking about a series without a single bad entry, no fillers, and no movie you pretend doesn't exist. Mad Max is one of them. Two things stand out. An incredible singular vision and breathtaking practical stunts and effects. George Miller has directed every Mad Max film except parts of Thunderdome. Game recognizes Game. He's praised John Wick's [music] action and choreography. He knows a thing or two about keeping the danger real. The rule is if the audience doesn't feel the weight of the hit, the stunt doesn't count. The stunts aren't designed to look dangerous. They are dangerous. This is the DNA. You can see this philosophy in the eyes of the crew. During the road warrior, cinematographer deem Semler built a tiny platform on the side of the interceptor to film the close-ups. At high [music] speeds, some metal would scrape the asphalt and sparks flew inches away from the lens. [music] They didn't stop filming. They kept driving because in Miller's world, that danger is the point. Once you've seen action made this way, you notice it immediately when it's not, which is why Furiosa stands [music] out. I really enjoyed Furiosa except for two things. The first is not relevant to this video. The second is that some of the scenes were clearly shot in virtual environments where the actors stand in front of large LED screens projecting the background. LED volume stages restrict camera movement and real depth. Sometimes it works, but most times it feels off. Look, if it work for you, you're probably one of the two dudes who keep insisting I'm AI. George Miller said they did it for safety, but they went overboard. Another thing they contributed to it was filming with the Air Alexa 65, which is a large sensor. Fury Road was filmed with a regular Alexa Super 35 size. That extra shallow depth of field in Furiosa is not the kind of background Miller worked decades to perfect. Even the day fornight scenes start to feel stage lit when they look great in Fury Road. Day for night is when they film in the day, but color grade to make it look like night. It's a fine line, kind of like the difference between good tailoring and bad. Thankfully, Furiosa redeems itself as a great film that [music] stands on its own. The stairway to nowhere scene took 78 days to shoot and involved 200 stunt performers daily. Anna Taylor Joy insisted on performing many of her own stunts. After all, she had big boots and a metal claw to fill. MadMax Fury Road is often considered to be the best film in the series. It also had visual effects to make the world grander, but it rarely feels out of place. Over 80% of the effects in Fury Road were practical. This included the Polecat stunts, [music] which were inspired by Chinese street performers. Miller thought it would be impossible, and he was leaning towards CGI. It was the stunt team led by Guy Norris who went off in secret, built a prototype, practiced for months, and filmed a demo to prove it could be done safely for real. They were actually swinging on 20ft poles at 50 mph. Many stunt performers rotated out due to exhaustion and injury. The flamethrowing guitar was 100% functional. It weighed over 100 lbs and the whammy bar actually controlled the flames. Even though they were stunt doubles for the actors, they still did many risky stunts. [music] The lead pair clash repeatedly due to the physical and emotional stress of production. They reconcile later because the movie worked. Here's a thing all film directors can relate to. When a movie bombs, it's their fault. But when it works, everyone assumes credit. When a great director like Miller does it over decades, that stops the noise. At that point, you're not guessing anymore. You're looking at a philosophy. Every Mad Max film is a choice, not a compromise. And nowhere is that philosophy clearer than in the film that splits fans in half. Thunderdome is the most polarizing film in the franchise. It introduced kids to the plot, had a PG-13 rating, and Tina Turner, which I personally think was a genius move. Thunderdome resembles Star Wars more than the films before it or after it. But as a standalone film, you can't deny it's a solid entertainer. After Byron Kennedy's death, Miller intentionally softened the tone and shared directing duties with George Ogleby. What's special about Thunderdome? It enlarges the world the first two [music] films set and introduces us to post-apocalyptic problems. In fact, most post-apocalyptic films owe their look and feel to the Mad Max universe. The Thunderdome structure was physically built, not a set extension. Actors and stunt performers trained inside it for weeks on wirework and combat. The world building is on another level. Without Thunderdome, the scale of Fury Road can't be justified. Miller and his team invented a functional economy based on methane. The imaginative detail of the master blaster pair controlling power via a literal underworld of pigs that shows that humans will find a way to create complex social structures, even if it's disgusting. Tina Turner as a CEO had to wear a costume made of brass that weighed more than 100 lb. She never complained, but she sang. It's also the only film that has that 80s vibe and polish. kind of like that odd fifth child, the one that keeps the others honest by refusing to follow the rules. Thunderdome proves Miller could build a society. But the film before it proved he could choreograph a war. The second film in the franchise was sadly renamed The Road Warrior in the US because the distributors assumed no one knew who Mad Max was. I'll be honest, this is my personal favorite, even over Fury Road, but you probably saw that coming. The Road Warrior is the template for the entire franchise. [music] Incredible action, stunts, and editing. If you want to know how out of touch Hollywood studios are, think about this. There is no Academy Award for stunts [music] or practical effects. Never has been. And no movie deserves it more than The Road Warrior. It's so effective that for a moment you actually wish you lived in that world, and then your popcorn runs out and you come back to your senses. [music] This world isn't heroic. It's unforgiving. The stunt team was operating on a different level because they had a point to make. They finally had a little more money to play with and they decided the best way to spend it was to risk their lives. In the middle of a chase, a stuntman was meant to land safely on a pile of boxes, but he overshot them. That stuntman was Guy Norris, who later did Fury Road. He actually broke his leg in that take. Several crashes were unplanned, but left in the film. [music] Injuries halted production multiple times. No second chances meant the limited coverage forced longer takes and wider framing. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; There was nowhere to hide mistakes. Compare that to the shallow depth of field shots in Furiosa. That's where the danger went. Watching the Road Warrior is like having an adrenaline drip in one arm and gasoline in the other. So, what order should you watch the franchise in? Honestly, watch it backward. Start with Furiosa. Then, Fury Road hits harder because her arc feels more meaningful and pointant. Then, move to Thunderdome as a sort of light-hearted plet cleanser before hitting the road warrior. This time, every stun lands twice as hard because you know exactly what this world is and what's in store in the future. And there is a specific reason I recommend saving the original 1979 MadMax for the very end. Once you've seen the first four, this one doesn't feel small, it feels inevitable. It's when the first of the last V8s switched on back in time and director George Miller had zero dollars and everything to lose. A lot of people call it the weakest film. Not if you watch it the way I recommend. This way you get to see the why of it all. Especially why danger is baked into every Mad Max film. Their goal was simple. Make the fastest action movie ever filmed. Their backup plan was even simpler. There wasn't one. They didn't have Hollywood money. George Miller was an ER doctor in Sydney who raised part of the $350,000 budget by working extra shifts. He had already watched people die for a living and he wanted the audience to feel that physical [music] impact. They didn't have insurance. If someone got hurt, the film was over. If the movie didn't work, there was no franchise to fall back on. This was guerilla filmm in its craziest form. To keep the costs low, many of the biker gang members were real local bikers. Some crew members were paid in beer. Mel Gibson was paid $10,000. There were no permits. The landscape was unforgiving. And when people were hurt, Miller personally stepped in because he was qualified to. George Miller used his own Mazda van in the opening chase. The same van he used to transport the crew. It was destroyed on camera. Kawasaki loaned them the bikes. Some of them never went back. The MFP uniforms were made of vinyl because leather was too expensive. In some highway shoots, real police reportedly mistook staged crashes for real accidents and nearly intervened. Later, they became fans. The film wasn't even meant to be post-apocalyptic. that became the setting because Miller couldn't afford real locations or sets. Now he could use abandoned buildings and empty roads. [music] The scarcity forced him to be brilliant. Influenced by the visual storytelling of Buster Keaton Hitchcock, the chariot race and Benhur and the relentless pace [music] of Steven Spielberg's duel, Miller structured his action like a medical emergency. There was no time for clever dialogue, only reaction. Against all logic, it worked. MadMax feels less like a be movie and more like an art film. While US distributors were embarrassed by it and barely gave it a release, the rest of the world caught fire. For 20 years, MadMax held the Guinness World Record for the highest box office grosstobudget ratio, grossing over $100 million. The MadMax universe still looks like a billion bucks because nothing about it was safe. Danger wasn't sprinkled later like salt. It was baked in from the [music] start. When most action movies pretend to show risk, MadMax was made by people who were living inside it. If it didn't work for real, it didn't work at all. It is why 45 years later, we await the next one with baited breath. Wasteland is coming [music] and now you know exactly what to look for. Support this channel and watch my film.

