In 1973, a major American studio decided to spend a million dollars to market a martial arts movie that only cost 850,000 to make. They roped in the biggest star they could find. In front of the camera, he moved so fast he could barely keep up. And behind it, he rewrote the script so fast the writer was always one page behind. By every analyst's estimation, Enter the Dragon should have been a joke. Instead, it became a global phenomenon that redefined action movies forever. In this video, I'm going to break down the incredible precision, the pain, and the raw electricity that makes Enter the Dragon still look like a billion bucks. To understand why this film works, you have to look at what came before it. Enter the Dragon didn't come out of nowhere. Martial arts films were already huge hits in Hong Kong and Southeast Asia. These movies were dominated by the Shaw Brothers and were often shot on colorful theatrical sets with stagey choreography. Characters flew through the air on visible wire sometimes, but to most foreign audiences, these movies were grindhouse filler. While this was going on, Bruce Lee was living a completely different story. Born in San Francisco and raised in Hong Kong, he was frequently involved in street fights. His parents pushed him towards training to discipline him. He began studying under the legendary Ip Man. That's where he learned the foundation, close-range combat, efficiency, and directness. But even then, he couldn't keep out of trouble. So, his parents sent him back to America before he got arrested or worse. He landed in Seattle with almost no money, started teaching martial arts in parking lots and back rooms. Somewhere between washing dishes, studying philosophy, and challenging other fighters, he decided he wasn't just going to master martial arts, he was going to reinvent how the world saw kung fu. And movies were the way. He had some visibility as Kato in The Green Hornet, but that didn't translate into better opportunities. Studios liked his presence, but they didn't see him as a leading man. At best, he was being offered side roles and stereotypes. So, by 1971, he made a calculated move, go where he could actually be a star. What he didn't fully expect was that Hong Kong already knew who he was. The Green Hornet had been a surprise hit there. In the US, he was a sidekick, but in Hong Kong, he was the main attraction. So, when he returned, Golden Harvest, a rising studio looking to compete with the Shaw Brothers, took the gamble and cast him in The Big Boss. It exploded and broke box office records. Audiences hadn't seen anything like him. His speed, his intensity, the raw physicality, no wirework, looked like real fighting. After Fist of Fury, he was the biggest name in Asian cinema. He grew so powerful, he wrote, directed, and starred in Way of the Dragon against Chuck Norris. Its success got Hollywood's attention. Warner Brothers saw an opportunity to make it more palatable to a Western audience, the plot was inspired by James Bond and the Terry and the Pirates comic strip, where the character Colonel Lee is a US AF officer who helps break up a heroin smuggling ring, which results in the arrest of its head, the president of a foreign country. They titled the project Blood and Steel and presented it to Concord, Bruce Lee's own production company. They hoped it would feature karate. That's like asking a Texas pit master to host a TV special on the benefits of a vegan lifestyle. Bruce Lee insisted and fought for the name Enter the Dragon. Why? He was born in the year of the Dragon. The Way of the Dragon was his way of displaying a glimpse of his martial arts philosophy, and Enter the Dragon was his way of entering America. He knew this was just another B movie, but it was a chance nonetheless. He had enough star power to win this battle, and Little Dragon got his way. He spent weeks refining the choreography to ensure every movement had a purpose. This focus on efficiency is exactly why the film feels modern even today. To any true student of martial arts, Enter the Dragon is pure bliss, as close to a religious experience as cinema can provide. Of course, you have to ignore the plot entirely, just like he did. Lee plays a Shaolin martial artist recruited by British intelligence to infiltrate a crime lord's private island under the guise of a martial arts tournament. Sound familiar? He barely needed to act. There are stories of him insisting on multiple takes, not because something looked wrong, but because it didn't feel right. One of the most famous examples is the opening Shaolin Temple sequence. It's shockingly precise and Spartan. Today, we'd recognize this as MMA. Both fighters are even wearing what looks like early MMA gear, and the fight ends with Lee locking in an armbar, something you'd usually see in judo or jujitsu. Many people point to this moment as the birth of MMA. Of course, the studio didn't notice any of this, even though it was happening right in front of them. So, naturally, they did what studios do best when they get nervous. They played it safe with the casting. John Saxon was cast to provide a familiar face for American audiences. Jim Kelly was brought in to resonate with the burgeoning blaxploitation genre. He got the best lines, in my opinion. I'll be too busy looking good. Yang Sze stands out as Bolo, and of course, by now everyone knows Jackie Chan's super brief moments in the film as a stuntman who really got hit in the face. For most of the actors, they had their best roles in this movie, but the film belongs to Bruce Lee. His physical presence is so intense that you can't look away. He also moved fast, which was a problem. To help with this, director of photography Gilbert Hubbs used an Arriflex 35 2C camera. It had two major benefits. First, it allowed the camera operator to see exactly what the lens saw while filming, which was crucial for framing Bruce Lee's lightning-fast movements. Second, while the industry standard is 24 frames per second, Lee's strikes often appeared as a blur or were missed entirely by the camera. To resolve this, they raised the frame rate to 32 frames per second. The goal was not slow motion, but by filming at 32 FPS and playing the footage back at the standard 24 FPS, the action was slowed down just enough to remain discernible to the human eye without looking like obvious slow motion. To make the movie look more expensive, Hubbs tracked down a set of Panavision C-series anamorphic lenses from a local Hong Kong rental house. This made it one of the first productions in Hong Kong to combine the mobility of the Aero Flex with the high-end anamorphic look. Because the budget was relatively low for a Hollywood production, they had to be resourceful. The sets were built in Hong Kong and a nearby island with a mix of traditional craftsmanship and low-cost materials. They hired hundreds of extras for the massive tournament scenes. Some of these extras were actual local gang members. A few of them stepped up to challenge Bruce Lee to real fights during breaks. He reportedly obliged them and ended those encounters quickly. The danger was not limited to the extras. Bruce Lee was also bitten by a cobra, which thankfully had its venom sacs removed. During the sequence where O'Hara attacks with broken bottles, a real glass bottle was used by mistake. Bruce Lee was cut badly and required stitches. The most brilliant decision was to have the final confrontation in a room of mirrors. They used over 8,000 mirrors and it was a nightmare to hide the camera and the lights, but it was worth it. The result is a scene that feels almost dreamlike and psychological, elevating it into something profound. These are the aspects of the film that Bruce Lee was proud of. What's your style? You can call it the art of fighting without fighting. Bruce Lee wanted the audience to understand that martial arts was about self-mastery, not just violence. In the film, he never looks like he's enjoying the fight. He looks like he's performing a duty, like doing the dishes. Lalo Schifrin, who had already composed the iconic Mission: Impossible theme, was hired to create the score. He brought a sophisticated jazz fusion sound that was entirely new to the genre. The music sounds expensive and international, which helped raise the production quality. Overall, the studio was amazed by the movie, but what really changed the game was another martial arts film. Five Fingers of Death was released in the US in March 1973. It became an overnight sensation topping the box office. The studio realized their movie was bigger and better, so they raised the marketing budget to over a million dollars. Enter the Dragon was released in August of 1973 just weeks after the tragic and sudden death of Bruce Lee. The timing was bittersweet, but it turned the film into a monument. Not only was it a big hit in America and Europe, but worldwide as well, all the way to India and even Iran, where it played in a single theater daily until 1979. Adjusted for inflation, the film's worldwide gross is estimated to be over two billion dollars. It launched a worldwide martial arts craze and paved the way for every action star from Jackie Chan to Keanu Reeves in just about every country making movies. If modern martial arts movies don't hit the same, it's probably because they lost the philosophy. Now, it's mostly about the stunts. Many action directors rely on digital effects and hyperkinetic editing, which strips the weight out of every punch. That's what happens when you trade culture for choreography. But when you watch Enter the Dragon, you feel the momentum of centuries of thought distilled and the uncompromising vision of a man who refused to let the world make him smaller. The dragon didn't just enter, he stayed forever. And that is why Enter the Dragon still looks like a billion bucks. Support this channel and watch my film.

