In 1966, the American Western was taken to a graveyard and shot in the face by three men. What should have taken 30 seconds is stretched to 6 minutes of screen time. No one moves. No one speaks. Music replaces the sound of a ticking clock until the moment the Western finally breaks. Because up until then, the cowboy had a moral compass. He rode in, fixed the problem, and rode out. Then we got bored and things got murky. Now when he rode in, you weren't sure if he was there to rescue the girl or shoot her for having the wrong last name. He was still a hero. He just sent an invoice afterward. That moral compass was barely hanging on. Then Sergio Leone showed up and smashed it with a rock. Good and bad wasn't good enough or bad enough. So Leone looked at that world and decided what it really needed was ugly. He stops filming horizons and starts filming faces. And he found the right one early. Clint Eastwood wasn't cast for his dialogue. He was cast for his face. He could say nothing and still look like he was winning a fight. This created the myth of the man with no name, a man to whom good or bad didn't matter. It took three movies to get there. The first film, A Fistful of Dollars, was the proof of concept. Eastwood showed up with his own wardrobe, a cheap poncho, and a pocketful of cigars. He proved he could hold a frame just by standing in it, which is why in the second film, For a Few Dollars More, Leone pushed the camera closer. Many more faces, longer holds. Leone learned to tell a story with just the eyes, a whole visual language ready for whatever came next. And that next film was The Good, the Bad, and the Ugly. The Western is no longer about majestic vistas and the hope it brings. The face is the landscape and it's hopeless. Eastwood returned only because they paid him a lot more and gave him a share of the profits. He had to revisit the same role he'd done twice before. You could say this was a prequel to the earlier films because Blondie assembles his iconic outfit in this film. Lee Van Cleef also returned. His hawkish face tells a story of a long hard life even before he draws his gun. Leone cast Eli Wallach for pure chaotic energy and gave him a lot of freedom to develop his character. The story takes place during the American Civil War, but it barely matters to these men. In this world, you didn't want to be the hero. You wanted the gold. They rarely show anger when betrayed and almost never show remorse even when they witness horrific war crimes. The look of the film was heavily influenced by Francisco Goya's stark war paintings and the vast landscapes of Spain. Leone viewed his characters as animals operating in a wasteland. You watch them sweat, bleed, and burn under the sun. Civil War photographs by Mathew Brady and Alexander Gardner influenced the look of the soldiers. Everyone looks worn down, even the rich look like they've lost something. To bring home this mythically gritty world, Leone and cinematographer Tonino Delli Colli decided to film using Techniscope, a format that used half the film stock but still gave them a widescreen frame. Half the negative made it cheaper, but when blown up for theaters, it gave the image a rougher, grainier texture. Techniscope is different from Cinemascope in that it uses spherical lenses. So, you don't see oval bokeh or blue lens flares or anamorphic mumps. This choice is why Leone's close-ups remain perfectly sharp and undistorted. You can see every pore because the aperture was stopped down to get that deep focus look. With this system, he could hold an extreme close-up of a face in the foreground while keeping a tiny figure far away in perfect focus. The message is, "No one escapes anyone here." And that includes the actors, many of whom were alarmed that the production didn't take their safety that seriously. Eli Wallach nearly died three times. First, he accidentally drank acid that had been left in a prop bottle. Then, a runaway horse dragged him with his hands tied behind his back. And finally, during the train scene, a massive iron step on a passing car missed his skull by an inch. You could say Leone was more focused on the visual language to worry about actor comfort. He locks the camera down and composes the frame so actors move inside it instead of chasing them with coverage. When he does move, it's slow and deliberate. He jumps between extreme wide shots and extreme close-ups with almost no middle ground, so you can feel the isolation of the landscape and the pressure between people. When Tuco forces Blondie through the desert, Leone keeps jumping from the desert to the cracked, peeling skin on Clint Eastwood's face. By forcing your eyes to reckon with this sight, he creates a physical sensation of oppressiveness using Blondie's face. Look at how Leone handles Tuco's arrival at the gun store. Information is only revealed when necessary. For example, as soon as Tuco enters, he should have seen the guns in front, but the story requires him to go for the other ones first. Realistically, he would have gone straight for the gun he wanted and got out as fast as he could. But the scene stretches every moment because we are desperate to know what's going to happen next. The sign he takes at the start ends up shoved into the shopkeeper's mouth. A literal sign to keep his mouth shut. It's funny, but very informative. In this scene, you learn how good Tuco really is, and you already know the other two are just as good. That sets up for an exciting finish. But before that can happen, there is one more piece of the Leone film language that needs to fall into place, and that is music. Ennio Morricone and Leone weren't just partners, they were old classmates. Usually, a composer watches the finished movie and writes music to fit the scenes. But for Leone, that was backwards. He had Morricone write and record the score before they ever set foot on set. Leone didn't give notes about keys or scales, he talked about animals. For the main theme, he wanted something that sounded like a coyote's howl. Morricone delivered exactly that. Many of the actors came from different parts of the world, and like the other films in the trilogy, it was dubbed later in post. On set, Leone would haul massive speakers and blast the finished score while the cameras were rolling. Imagine being Clint Eastwood standing in that heat with this operatic howl vibrating in your chest. The music became the director's assistant. It told the actors exactly how slow to walk, how long to stare, and when to blink. The music dictates when scenes begin and end, and when it does, something brutal always happens. All this film craft leads up to one incredible climax at the Sad Hill Cemetery, which wasn't a real location. It was built by Spanish soldiers. Thousands of graves laid out in perfect circles, all leading to a stone arena at the center. Tuco runs around it, and the camera tracks him with a long telephoto lens from the center, flattening the space and making the graveyard feel like it's closing in. A lot of this visual grammar owes a debt to Kurosawa. Leone was a huge fan, but here he pushes those ideas in his own direction. Leone turns this moment into pure opera, and after all that running, all the sweat, all the music winding tighter and tighter, everything arrives at the simplest image imaginable, So, we can take in the geography. Three men, one circle, one shot. But, before the shot, Leone decides to reduce the entire Western genre to a staring contest. He lays out the final duel like it's been plotted on graph paper. The cuts follow a pattern you can feel even if you don't notice it. He starts wide, then steps in closer, then closer again, until you're stuck inside their faces and their guns. The same elements repeat, but the cuts get shorter each time. Morricone's score sets the tempo and the edit rides it like a rail. By the time the gun goes off, the release is pure euphoria. His score is widely considered one of the greatest pieces of music in cinema history. And once you've seen the sequence, you'll never forget it. The Good, the Bad and the Ugly was a massive hit worldwide. It was so successful they had to give the genre a name. The critics called them spaghetti westerns as a put-down. But, Leone turned that insult into a brand of cool Hollywood couldn't touch. He returned with two more films after this without Eastwood, but with new faces. Once Upon a Time in the West and Duck, You Sucker. If you're looking at the evolution of his style, the real trilogy begins with The Ugly and ends with The Sucker. They have different actors and different settings, but they push the same ideas in totally new directions. It's the final form of the Leone style and there's only ever been one. Subscribe and watch my film.

