onal power which reinforces the idea of oppression. Even the cars are boxy with sharp lines. Almost every location and prop choice communicate a power structure without dialogue. It also photographs well in harsh light. The sharp edges create strong shadows. Characters look small against the massive walls and columns which by itself feels indifferent to human life. Anyone can be erased or any history [music] rewritten. And we absolutely feel this way on a deep level. For why else would we buy into the idea that a vacation on Mars, a hostile environment, is a pleasant escape from life on Earth. Today's billionaires seem to be pedling the same idea. Total recall predicts a lot of cool tech available right now. Joystick driven cars, automated cars, the red pill, implants in your brain, or whatever else, even vertical video. Everything on Earth is normal but fake. The perfect woman. The perfect cab driver. Steady jobs. Everything at bars is terrible but real. Rachel Tickotton is no Sharon Stone. The cab driver has a secret. And there are no employees, only slaves. In this lopsided world, Arnold plays Douglas Quaid, a construction worker who dreams of going to Mars. That would offend his incredible wife, though. So, as plan B, he visits a company called Recall with a K that promises to implant artificial memories of a perfect adventure to Mars instead. As an add-on, he gets to roleplay as a secret agent. &gt;&gt; How much is that? &gt;&gt; Something goes wrong, or maybe something goes right. The film never fully confirms either way, [music] and this uncertainty becomes the engine of everything that follows. From that point on, every gunfight, chase, and betrayal carries a second question underneath. Is any of this actually happening? So what Total Recall is really about is whether you can trust your own mind or identity. Today that concern is a lot more immediate than back in 1990 when the internet barely existed for most people. Artificial intelligence wasn't part of everyday conversation. In the blink of an eye, we scroll through feed shaped by algorithms, watch synthetic videos that blur truth and fiction, and argue over whether my voice is real. The movie central fear that your life might be constructed for you feels like a warning that arrived early, but that's in hindsight. They had to sell this vision in 1990. The team built a large miniature that was 14 ft tall and 40 ft wide. It was constructed of wood and plaster and lots of real dirt. The camera glides through it in a realistic, nauseating way because it's real [music] movement. They filmed those sets using Vista Vision, which provided a higher resolution than standard 35mm film stock. This is even more demanding for the artist because any tiny [music] mistakes show up on a cinema screen. The audience may not consciously analyze it, but the eye registers all the layers of light, texture, and movement that's [music] real. Rob Button's makeup effects push that tactile reality even further. He understood that a machine feels real when it has mechanical flaws. The Fat Lady mask is a masterpiece of engineering. It consisted of several motorized segments that were controlled by a team of technicians. When the mass splits open, you see the internal hydraulics and the physical clicking of the parts. It proves to the audience that what they are seeing actually [music] exists. The mutant leader growing out of another man's torso was a fully animatronic puppet coordinated by a team beneath the frame. You can see the slight irregularities in the blinking and skin movement. In the X-ray wall sequence, the team filmed the actors using reference cameras and then matched the animated skeletons to the weight and timing of their human steps. Even the most stylized moments of the film feel connected to the world. These imperfections are not flaws. They are proof. The lighting not only has to bring out all this without ruining the illusion, but also has to reinforce the themes of class struggle and corporate control. Mars is bathed in bright red tones. Earth is blue. The system is black and gray. Real people are colorful and unique. Mars looks cool because the location chosen has character. Not once do we question it. The people living there actually feel like they live there. Feels like a place you can really visit. Total Recall became a massive hit because it delivered a level of production value in a direction that people had never seen. But critics at the time were shocked by the violence. Paul Beerhovven had to cut several violent scenes to avoid an X-rating because a practical gore [music] was considered too realistic. He did not want a sanitized version of the future. The other complaint by critics was that they thought Arnold was the wrong guy to play the lead. He was already a global action star, but in this film, he hardly shows his biceps. [music] He insisted on doing many of his own stunts. During a fight scene, he had to smash through a glass window. The explosive charge went off at the wrong time, and he cut his arm. He finished the scene while bleeding. This is my opinion, but when everything else in Total Recall is larger than life, then Arnold makes perfect sense. And after that first horrible visual, you have Sharon Stone, who can complain? [music] Maybe Michael Ironside is Rich Victor, whose arrangement the sequel didn't dare to repeat. The sound design and music are the final pieces of the puzzle. Hearing Mars is half the immersion. Jerry Goldsmith's score doesn't question whether the story is epic. It declares it. It is pulpy, exaggerated, occasionally darkly funny. Mirhovven understands the absurdity of a man with a mutant growing out of his stomach whispering, "Open [snorts] your mind." &gt;&gt; The film doesn't apologize for anything. The 2012 remake offers a useful but painful [music] comparison. heavy on digital environments and lens flare. It feels strangely smaller. Everything feels choreographed rather than eruptive. [music] It has none of the satire. The original mocks the idea that you can buy a better version of yourself. The news reports on Mars show a population being lied to by their government. [music] The film trusts the intelligence of the audience to see the truth beneath the absurdity. If you sugarcoat reality, it's nobody's reality. Make no mistake, Total Recall remains a product of its era. unapologetically 1990 in style and attitude, yet is a one-of-a-kind experience. Instead of dating the film in a negative way, those qualities give it a lasting personality. It just does not look or feel like any other movie, and it talks to us. We from the future more than 35 years later. This is why Total Recall still looks like a billion bucks. Not because it predicted the future perfectly or whatever, but because it built one you want to touch. [music] Support this channel and watch my film.

